# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: effect-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **monad** is a triple $(T,\eta ,\mu )$ consisting of a functor *T* from a category to itself and two natural transformations $\eta ,\mu$ that satisfy versions of the associativity and unitality axioms.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Equivalently, a monad is a monoid in the category of endofunctors of some fixed category (an endofunctor is a functor mapping a category to itself).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, if $F,G$ are functors adjoint to each other, then $T=G\circ F$ together with $\eta ,\mu$ determined by the adjoint relation is a monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] A monad as a tool for studying algebraic gadgets; for example, a group can be described by a certain monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monads are used in the theory of pairs of adjoint functors, and they generalize closure operators on partially ordered sets to arbitrary categories.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monads are also useful in the theory of datatypes, the denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and in functional programming languages, allowing languages without mutable state to do things such as simulate for-loops; see Monad (functional programming).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] A monad is also called, especially in old literature, a **triple**, **triad**, **standard construction** and **fundamental construction**.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] A monad is a certain type of endofunctor.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, if F and G are a pair of adjoint functors, with F left adjoint to G , then the composition $G\circ F$ is a monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] If F and G are inverse to each other, the corresponding monad is the identity functor.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In general, adjunctions are not equivalences—they relate categories of different natures.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The monad theory matters as part of the effort to capture what it is that adjunctions 'preserve'.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The other half of the theory, of what can be learned likewise from consideration of $F\circ G$ , is discussed under the dual theory of *comonads*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Throughout this article, C denotes a category.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] A *monad* on C consists of an endofunctor $T\colon C\to C$ together with two natural transformations: $\eta \colon 1_{C}\to T$ (where $1_{C}$ denotes the identity functor on C ) and $\mu \colon T^{2}\to T$ (where $T^{2}$ is the functor $T\circ T$ from C to C ).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The first axiom is akin to the associativity in monoids if we think of $\mu$ as the monoid's binary operation, and the second axiom is akin to the existence of an identity element (which we think of as given by $\eta$ ).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Indeed, a monad on C can alternatively be defined as a monoid in the category $\mathbf {End} _{C}$ whose objects are the endofunctors of C and whose morphisms are the natural transformations between them, with the monoidal structure induced by the composition of endofunctors.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The *power set monad* is a monad ${\mathcal {P}}$ on the category $\mathbf {Set}$ : For a set A let $T(A)$ be the power set of A and for a function $f\colon A\to B$ let $T(f)$ be the function between the power sets induced by taking direct images under f .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For every set A , we have a map $\eta _{A}\colon A\to T(A)$ , which assigns to every $a\in A$ the singleton $\{a\}$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The axioms of a monad are formally similar to the monoid axioms.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In fact, monads are a type of monoid object; they are precisely the monoids among endofunctors $\operatorname {End} (C)$ , with the multiplication given by composition of endofunctors.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Composition of monads is not, in general, a monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, the double power set functor ${\mathcal {P}}\circ {\mathcal {P}}$ does not admit any monad structure.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The categorical dual definition is a formal definition of a *comonad* (or *cotriple*); this can be said quickly in the terms that a comonad for a category C is a monad for the opposite category $C^{\mathrm {op} }$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] It is therefore a functor U from C to itself, with a set of axioms for *counit* and *comultiplication* that come from reversing the arrows everywhere in the definition just given.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monads are to monoids as comonads are to *comonoids*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Every set is a comonoid in a unique way, so comonoids are less familiar in abstract algebra than monoids; however, comonoids in the category of vector spaces with its usual tensor product are important and widely studied under the name of coalgebras.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The notion of monad was invented by Roger Godement in 1958 under the name "standard construction".
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monad has been called "dual standard construction", "triple", "monoid" and "triad".
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The term "monad" is used at latest 1967, by Jean Bénabou.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The identity functor on a category C is a monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Its multiplication and unit are the identity function on the objects of C .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In fact, **any monad can be found as an explicit adjunction of functors** using the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ (the category of T -algebras).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] where both functors are given by sending a vector space *V* to its dual vector space $V^{*}:=\operatorname {Hom} (V,k)$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The associated monad sends a vector space *V* to its double dual $V^{**}$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] This monad is discussed, in much greater generality, by Kock (1970).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For categories arising from partially ordered sets $(P,\leq )$ (with a single morphism from x to y if and only if $x\leq y$ ), then the formalism becomes much simpler: adjoint pairs are Galois connections and monads are closure operators.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, let G be the forgetful functor from the category **Grp** of groups to the category **Set** of sets, and let F be the free group functor from the category of sets to the category of groups.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In this case, the associated monad $T=G\circ F$ takes a set X and returns the underlying set of the free group $\mathrm {Free} (X)$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] including any set X into the set $\mathrm {Free} (X)$ in the natural way, as strings of length 1.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] made out of a natural concatenation or 'flattening' of 'strings of strings'.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] This amounts to two natural transformations.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The preceding example about free groups can be generalized to any type of algebra in the sense of a variety of algebras in universal algebra.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Thus, every such type of algebra gives rise to a monad on the category of sets.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Importantly, the algebra type can be recovered from the monad (as the category of Eilenberg–Moore algebras), so monads can also be seen as generalizing varieties of universal algebras.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Another monad arising from an adjunction is when T is the endofunctor on the category of vector spaces which maps a vector space V to its tensor algebra $T(V)$ , and which maps linear maps to their tensor product.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] We then have a natural transformation corresponding to the embedding of V into its tensor algebra, and a natural transformation corresponding to the map from $T(T(V))$ to $T(V)$ obtained by simply expanding all tensor products.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Under mild conditions, functors not admitting a left adjoint also give rise to a monad, the so-called codensity monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Its codensity monad is the monad on sets sending any set *X* to the set of ultrafilters on *X*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] This and similar examples are discussed in Leinster (2013).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The following monads over the category of sets are used in denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and analogous constructions are used in functional programming.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The multiplication maps elements of X to themselves, and the two disjoint points in $(X_{*})_{*}$ to the one in $X_{*}$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In both functional programming and denotational semantics, the maybe monad models partial computations, that is, computations that may fail.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Given a set S , the endofunctor of the **state monad** maps each set X to the set of functions $S\to S\times X$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In functional programming and denotational semantics, the state monad models stateful computations.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Given a set E , the endofunctor of the **reader** or **environment monad** maps each set X to the set of functions $E\to X$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Thus, the endofunctor of this monad is exactly the hom functor $\mathrm {Hom} (E,-)$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The component of the unit at X maps each element $x\in X$ to the constant function $e\mapsto x$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The multiplication maps a two-variable function $f:E\to (E\to X)$ to its "diagonal component" $(e\mapsto f(e,e)):E\to X$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In functional programming and denotational semantics, the environment monad models computations with access to some read-only data.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The **list** or **nondeterminism monad** maps a set *X* to the set of finite sequences (i.e., lists) with elements from *X*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The unit maps an element *x* in *X* to the singleton list [x].
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The multiplication concatenates a list of lists into a single list.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In functional programming, the list monad is used to model nondeterministic computations.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The covariant powerset monad is also known as the **set monad**, and is also used to model nondeterministic computation.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Given a monad $(T,\eta ,\mu )$ on a category C , it is natural to consider *T -algebras*, i.e., objects of C acted upon by T in a way which is compatible with the unit and multiplication of the monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] T -algebras form a category called the *Eilenberg–Moore category* and denoted by $C^{T}$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, for the free group monad discussed above, a T -algebra is a set X together with a map from the free group generated by X towards X subject to associativity and unitality conditions.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Such a structure is equivalent to saying that X is a group itself.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Another example is the ***distribution monad*** ${\mathcal {D}}$ on the category of sets.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] It is defined by sending a set X to the set of functions $f:X\to [0,1]$ with finite support and such that their sum is equal to 1 .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, ${\text{Sym}}^{\bullet }(R^{\oplus n})\cong R[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ where the R -algebra on the right is considered as a module.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Then, an algebra over this monad are commutative R -algebras.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] There is an analogous construction for commutative $\mathbb {S}$ -algebraspg 113 which gives commutative A -algebras for a commutative $\mathbb {S}$ -algebra A .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] If ${\mathcal {M}}_{A}$ is the category of A -modules, then the functor $\mathbb {P$ is the monad given by $\mathbb {P} (M)=\bigvee _{j\geq 0}M^{j}/\Sigma _{j}$ where $M^{j}=M\wedge _{A}\cdots \wedge _{A}M$ j -times.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Then there is an associated category ${\mathcal {C}}_{A}$ of commutative A -algebras from the category of algebras over this monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] As was mentioned above, any adjunction gives rise to a monad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] whose left adjoint sends an object *X* to the free *T*-algebra *T*(*X*).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Then the above free–forgetful adjunction involving the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ is a terminal object in $\mathbf {Adj} (C,T)$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] An initial object is the Kleisli category, which is by definition the full subcategory of $C^{T}$ consisting only of free *T*-algebras, i.e., *T*-algebras of the form $T(x)$ for some object *x* of *C*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] i.e., *G*(*Y*) can be naturally endowed with a *T*-algebra structure for any *Y* in *D*.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The adjunction is called a **monadic adjunction** if the first functor ${\tilde {G}}$ yields an equivalence of categories between *D* and the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ .
[src:effect-systems/comonad] By extension, a functor $G\colon D\to C$ is said to be **monadic** if it has a left adjoint F forming a monadic adjunction.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, the free–forgetful adjunction between groups and sets is monadic, since algebras over the associated monad are groups, as was mentioned above.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In general, knowing that an adjunction is monadic allows one to reconstruct objects in *D* out of objects in *C* and the *T*-action.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] For example, the forgetful functor from the category of compact Hausdorff spaces to sets is monadic.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] However the forgetful functor from all topological spaces to sets is not conservative since there are continuous bijective maps (between non-compact or non-Hausdorff spaces) that fail to be homeomorphisms.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Thus, this forgetful functor is not monadic.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The dual version of Beck's theorem, characterizing comonadic adjunctions, is relevant in different fields such as topos theory and topics in algebraic geometry related to descent.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] for a ring homomorphism $A\to B$ between commutative rings.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] This adjunction is comonadic, by Beck's theorem, if and only if *B* is faithfully flat as an *A*-module.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] It thus allows to descend *B*-modules, equipped with a descent datum (i.e., an action of the comonad given by the adjunction) to *A*-modules.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The resulting theory of faithfully flat descent is widely applied in algebraic geometry.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monads are used in functional programming to express types of sequential computation (sometimes with side-effects).
[src:effect-systems/comonad] See monads in functional programming, and the more mathematically oriented Wikibook module b:Haskell/Category theory.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monads are used in the denotational semantics of impure functional and imperative programming languages.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] In categorical logic, an analogy has been drawn between the monad-comonad theory, and modal logic via closure operators, interior algebras, and their relation to models of S4 and intuitionistic logics.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] Monad is also defined in a any weak 2-category, which is defined as a lax 2-functor from terminal category $\mathbb {1}$ to 2-category Cat.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The theory of 2-monads was introduced by Blackwell–Kelly–Power, and 2-monads without prefixes are usually a strict notion.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] A notion that weakens monad laws so that they hold "up to coherent invertible modifications" is called pseudomonad.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] While there are attempts to define monad preserving composition only up to a noninvertible transformation, there is no obvious general notion of lax monad on a weak 2-category, since there is no good 2-category (or even a weak 3-category) of weak 2-categories that contain lax or oplax functors.
[src:effect-systems/comonad] The lax monad was first introduced by Bunge, but other definitions different from lax monad à la Bunge.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] In computing, an **effect system** is a formal system that describes the computational effects of computer programs, such as side effects.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] An effect system can be used to provide a compile-time check of the possible effects of the program.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] The effect system extends the notion of type to have an "effect" component, which comprises an **effect kind** and a **region**.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] The effect kind describes *what* is being done, and the region describes *with what* (parameters) it is being done.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] An effect system is typically an extension of a type system.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] The term "**type and effect system**" is sometimes used in this case.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] Often, a type of a value is denoted together with its effect as *type ! effect*, where both the type component and the effect component mention certain regions (for example, a type of a mutable memory cell is parameterized by the label of the memory region in which the cell resides).
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] The term "algebraic effect" follows from the type system.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] From a programmer's point of view, effects are useful as it allows for separating the implementation (*how*) of specific actions from the specification of what actions to perform.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] For example, an *ask name* effect can read from either the console, pop a window, or just return a default value.
[src:effect-systems/effect-system] The control flow can be described as a blend of *yield* (in that the execution continues) and *throw* (in that an unhandled effect propagates down until handled).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In functional programming, **monads** are a way to structure computations as a sequence of steps, where each step not only produces a value but also some extra information about the computation, such as a potential failure, non-determinism, or side effect.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] More formally, a monad is a type constructor M equipped with two operations, `return : <A>(a : A) -> M(A)` which lifts a value into the monadic context, and `bind : <A,B>(m_a : M(A), f : A -> M(B)) -> M(B)` which chains monadic computations.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In simpler terms, monads can be thought of as interfaces implemented on type constructors, that allow for functions to abstract over various type constructor variants that implement monad (e.g.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Both the concept of a monad and the term originally come from category theory, where a monad is defined as an endofunctor with additional structure.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Research beginning in the late 1980s and early 1990s established that monads could bring seemingly disparate computer-science problems under a unified, functional model.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Category theory also provides a few formal requirements, known as the **monad laws**, which should be satisfied by any monad and can be used to verify monadic code.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Since monads make semantics explicit for a kind of computation, they can also be used to implement convenient language features.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Some languages, such as Haskell, even offer pre-built definitions in their core libraries for the general monad structure and common instances.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] "For a monad `m`, a value of type `m a` represents having access to a value of type `a` within the context of the monad." —C.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] More exactly, a monad can be used where unrestricted access to a value is inappropriate for reasons specific to the scenario.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the Maybe monad, it is because the value may not exist.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the IO monad, it is because the value may not be known yet, such as when the monad represents user input that will only be provided after a prompt is displayed.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In all cases the scenarios in which access makes sense are captured by the bind operation defined for the monad; for the Maybe monad a value is bound only if it exists, and for the IO monad a value is bound only after the previous operations in the sequence have been performed.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] With these elements, the programmer composes a sequence of function calls (a "pipeline") with several *bind* operators chained together in an expression.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Each function call transforms its input plain-type value, and the bind operator handles the returned monadic value, which is fed into the next step in the sequence.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Typically, the bind operator `>>=` may contain code unique to the monad that performs additional computation steps not available in the function received as a parameter.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Between each pair of composed function calls, the bind operator can inject into the monadic value `m a` some additional information that is not accessible within the function `f`, and pass it along down the pipeline.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] It can also exert finer control of the flow of execution, for example by calling the function only under some conditions, or executing the function calls in a particular order.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] One example of a monad is the `Maybe` type.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Undefined null results are one particular pain point that many procedural languages don't provide specific tools for dealing with, requiring use of the null object pattern or checks to test for invalid values at each operation to handle undefined values.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This causes bugs and makes it harder to build robust software that gracefully handles errors.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` type forces the programmer to deal with these potentially undefined results by explicitly defining the two states of a result: `Just ⌑result⌑`, or `Nothing`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] For example, the programmer might be constructing a parser, which is to return an intermediate result, or else signal a condition which the parser has detected, and which the programmer must also handle.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] With just a little extra functional spice on top, this `Maybe` type transforms into a fully-featured monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In most languages, the Maybe monad is also known as an option type, which is just a type that marks whether or not it contains a value.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Typically they are expressed as some kind of enumerated type.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In the Rust programming language it is called `Option<T>` and variants of this type can either be a value of generic type `T`, or the empty variant: `None`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `Option<T>` can also be understood as a "wrapping" type, and this is where its connection to monads comes in.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In languages with some form of the Maybe type, there are functions that aid in their use such as composing **monadic functions** with each other and testing if a Maybe contains a value.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In the following hard-coded example, a Maybe type is used as a result of functions that may fail, in this case the type returns nothing if there is a divide-by-zero.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] One such way to test whether or not a Maybe contains a value is to use `if` statements.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Monads can compose functions that return Maybe, putting them together.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Instead of repeating `Some` expressions, we can use something called a *bind* operator.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] (also known as "map", "flatmap", or "shove").
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This operation takes a monad and a function that returns a monad and runs the function on the inner value of the passed monad, returning the monad from the function.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In Haskell, there is an operator *bind*, or (`>>=`) that allows for this monadic composition in a more elegant form similar to function composition.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] With `>>=` available, `chainable_division` can be expressed much more succinctly with the help of anonymous functions (i.e. lambdas).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Notice in the expression below how the two nested lambdas each operate on the wrapped value in the passed `Maybe` monad using the bind operator.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] What has been shown so far is basically a monad, but to be more concise, the following is a strict list of qualities necessary for a monad as defined by the following section.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] These are the 3 things necessary to form a monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Other monads may embody different logical processes, and some may have additional properties, but all of them will have these three similar components.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The more common definition for a monad in functional programming, used in the above example, is actually based on a Kleisli triple ⟨T, η, μ⟩ rather than category theory's standard definition.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The two constructs turn out to be mathematically equivalent, however, so either definition will yield a valid monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Algebraically, this means any monad both gives rise to a category (called the Kleisli category) *and* a monoid in the category of functors (from values to computations), with monadic composition as a binary operator in the monoid and unit as identity in the monoid.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The value of the monad pattern goes beyond merely condensing code and providing a link to mathematical reasoning.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Whatever language or default programming paradigm a developer uses, following the monad pattern brings many of the benefits of purely functional programming.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] By reifying a specific kind of computation, a monad not only encapsulates the tedious details of that computational pattern, but it does so in a declarative way, improving the code's clarity.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] As monadic values explicitly represent not only computed values, but computed *effects*, a monadic expression can be replaced with its value in referentially transparent positions, much like pure expressions can be, allowing for many techniques and optimizations based on rewriting.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Typically, programmers will use bind to chain monadic functions into a sequence, which has led some to describe monads as "programmable semicolons", a reference to how many imperative languages use semicolons to separate statements.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] However, monads do not actually order computations; even in languages that use them as central features, simpler function composition can arrange steps within a program.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A monad's general utility rather lies in simplifying a program's structure and improving separation of concerns through abstraction.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The monad structure can also be seen as a uniquely mathematical and compile time variation on the decorator pattern.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Some monads can pass along extra data that is inaccessible to functions, and some even exert finer control over execution, for example only calling a function under certain conditions.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Because they let application programmers implement domain logic while offloading boilerplate code onto pre-developed modules, monads can even be considered a tool for aspect-oriented programming.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] One other noteworthy use for monads is isolating side-effects, like input/output or mutable state, in otherwise purely functional code.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Even purely functional languages *can* still implement these "impure" computations without monads, via an intricate mix of function composition and continuation-passing style (CPS) in particular.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] With monads though, much of this scaffolding can be abstracted away, essentially by taking each recurring pattern in CPS code and bundling it into a distinct monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] If a language does not support monads by default, it is still possible to implement the pattern, often without much difficulty.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] When translated from category-theory to programming terms, the monad structure is a generic concept and can be defined directly in any language that supports an equivalent feature for bounded polymorphism.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A concept's ability to remain agnostic about operational details while working on underlying types is powerful, but the unique features and stringent behavior of monads set them apart from other concepts.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Discussions of specific monads will typically focus on solving a narrow implementation problem since a given monad represents a specific computational form.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In some situations though, an application can even meet its high-level goals by using appropriate monads within its core logic.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The term "monad" in programming dates to the APL and J programming languages, which do tend toward being purely functional.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] However, in those languages, "monad" is only shorthand for a function taking one parameter (a function with two parameters being a "dyad", and so on).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The mathematician Roger Godement was the first to formulate the concept of a monad (dubbing it a "standard construction") in the late 1950s, though the term "monad" that came to dominate was popularized by category-theorist Saunders Mac Lane.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The form defined above using bind, however, was originally described in 1965 by mathematician Heinrich Kleisli in order to prove that any monad could be characterized as an adjunction between two (covariant) functors.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Starting in the 1980s, a vague notion of the monad pattern began to surface in the computer science community.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] According to programming language researcher Philip Wadler, computer scientist John C.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Reynolds anticipated several facets of it in the 1970s and early 1980s, when he discussed the value of continuation-passing style, of category theory as a rich source for formal semantics, and of the type distinction between values and computations.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The research language Opal, which was actively designed up until 1990, also effectively based I/O on a monadic type, but the connection was not realized at the time.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The computer scientist Eugenio Moggi was the first to explicitly link the monad of category theory to functional programming, in a conference paper in 1989, followed by a more refined journal submission in 1991.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In earlier work, several computer scientists had advanced using category theory to provide semantics for the lambda calculus.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Moggi's key insight was that a real-world program is not just a function from values to other values, but rather a transformation that forms *computations* on those values.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] When formalized in category-theoretic terms, this leads to the conclusion that monads are the structure to represent these computations.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Several others popularized and built on this idea, including Philip Wadler and Simon Peyton Jones, both of whom were involved in the specification of Haskell.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In particular, Haskell used a problematic "lazy stream" model up through v1.2 to reconcile I/O with lazy evaluation, until switching over to a more flexible monadic interface.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The Haskell community would go on to apply monads to many problems in functional programming, and in the 2010s, researchers working with Haskell eventually recognized that monads are applicative functors; and that both monads and arrows are monoids.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] At first, programming with monads was largely confined to Haskell and its derivatives, but as functional programming has influenced other paradigms, many languages have incorporated a monad pattern (in spirit if not in name).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Formulations now exist in Scheme, Perl, Python, Racket, Clojure, Scala, F#, and have also been considered for a new ML standard.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] One benefit of the monad pattern is bringing mathematical precision on the composition of computations.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Not only can the monad laws be used to check an instance's validity, but features from related structures (like functors) can be used through subtyping.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Returning to the `Maybe` example, its components were declared to make up a monad, but no proof was given that it satisfies the monad laws.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Though rarer in computer science, one can use category theory directly, which defines a monad as a functor with two additional natural transformations.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This is not always a major issue, however, especially when a monad is derived from a pre-existing functor, whereupon the monad inherits map automatically.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A monad's first transformation is actually the same unit from the Kleisli triple, but following the hierarchy of structures closely, it turns out unit characterizes an applicative functor, an intermediate structure between a monad and a basic functor.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In the applicative context, unit is sometimes referred to as **pure** but is still the same function.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The **List monad** naturally demonstrates how deriving a monad from a simpler functor can come in handy.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In many languages, a list structure comes pre-defined along with some basic features, so a `List` type constructor and append operator (represented with `++` for infix notation) are assumed as already given here.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] From here, applying a function iteratively with a list comprehension may seem like an easy choice for bind and converting lists to a full monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The difficulty with this approach is that bind expects monadic functions, which in this case will output lists themselves; as more functions are applied, layers of nested lists will accumulate, requiring more than a basic comprehension.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Now, these two procedures already promote `List` to an applicative functor.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] One application for this monadic list is representing nondeterministic computation.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `List` can hold results for all execution paths in an algorithm, then condense itself at each step to "forget" which paths led to which results (a sometimes important distinction from deterministic, exhaustive algorithms).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Another benefit is that checks can be embedded in the monad; specific paths can be pruned transparently at their first point of failure, with no need to rewrite functions in the pipeline.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A second situation where `List` shines is composing multivalued functions.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] For instance, the nth complex root of a number should yield n distinct complex numbers, but if another mth root is then taken of those results, the final m•n values should be identical to the output of the m•nth root.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `List` completely automates this issue away, condensing the results from each step into a flat, mathematically correct list.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Monads present opportunities for interesting techniques beyond just organizing program logic.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Monads can lay the groundwork for useful syntactic features while their high-level and mathematical nature enable significant abstraction.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Although using bind openly often makes sense, many programmers prefer a syntax that mimics imperative statements (called *do-notation* in Haskell, *perform-notation* in OCaml, *computation expressions* in F#, and *for comprehension* in Scala).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This is only syntactic sugar that disguises a monadic pipeline as a code block; the compiler will then quietly translate these expressions into underlying functional code.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Translating the `add` function from the `Maybe` into Haskell can show this feature in action.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A second example shows how `Maybe` can be used in an entirely different language: F#.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Every monad needs a specific implementation that meets the monad laws, but other aspects like the relation to other structures or standard idioms within a language are shared by all monads.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] As a result, a language or library may provide a general `Monad` interface with function prototypes, subtyping relationships, and other general facts.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Besides providing a head-start to development and guaranteeing a new monad inherits features from a supertype (such as functors), checking a monad's design against the interface adds another layer of quality control.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code can often be simplified even further through the judicious use of operators.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The map functional can be especially helpful since it works on more than just ad-hoc monadic functions; so long as a monadic function should work analogously to a predefined operator, map can be used to instantly "lift" the simpler operator into a monadic one.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The process could be taken even one step further by defining `add` not just for `Maybe`, but for the whole `Monad` interface.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] By doing this, any new monad that matches the structure interface and implements its own map will immediately inherit a lifted version of `add` too.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `Identity` does actually have valid uses though, such as providing a base case for recursive monad transformers.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] It can also be used to perform basic variable assignment within an imperative-style block.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Any collection with a proper append is already a monoid, but it turns out that `List` is not the only collection that also has a well-defined join and qualifies as a monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] As already mentioned, pure code should not have unmanaged side effects, but that does not preclude a program from *explicitly* describing and managing effects.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This idea is central to Haskell's **IO monad**, where an object of type `IO a` can be seen as describing an action to be performed in the world, optionally providing information about the world of type `a`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] An action that provides no information about the world has the type `IO ()`, "providing" the dummy value `()`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] When a programmer binds an `IO` value to a function, the function computes the next action to be performed based on the information about the world provided by the previous action (input from users, files, etc.).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Most significantly, because the value of the IO monad can only be bound to a function that computes another IO monad, the bind function imposes a discipline of a sequence of actions where the result of an action can only be provided to a function that will compute the next action to perform.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This means that actions which do not need to be performed never are, and actions that do need to be performed have a well defined sequence.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] For example, Haskell has several functions for acting on the wider file system, including one that checks whether a file exists and another that deletes a file.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The first is interested in whether a given file really exists, and as a result, outputs a Boolean value within the `IO` monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The second function, on the other hand, is only concerned with acting on the file system so the `IO` container it outputs is empty.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Another common situation is keeping a log file or otherwise reporting a program's progress.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, a programmer may want to log even more specific, technical data for later profiling or debugging.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The **Writer monad** can handle these tasks by generating auxiliary output that accumulates step-by-step.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] To show how the monad pattern is not restricted to primarily functional languages, this example implements a `Writer` monad in Java, stored in a class representing the `Writer` monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] An environment monad (also called a *reader monad* and a *function monad*) allows a computation to depend on values from a shared environment.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The monad type constructor maps a type T to functions of type *E* → *T*, where E is the type of the shared environment.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The ask operation is used to retrieve the current context, while local executes a computation in a modified subcontext.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] As in a state monad, computations in the environment monad may be invoked by simply providing an environment value and applying it to an instance of the monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Formally, a value in an environment monad is equivalent to a function with an additional, anonymous argument; return and bind are equivalent to the K and S combinators, respectively, in the SKI combinator calculus.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A state monad allows a programmer to attach state information of any type to a calculation.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Given any value type, the corresponding type in the state monad is a function which accepts a state, then outputs a new state (of type `s`) along with a return value (of type `t`).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This is similar to an environment monad, except that it also returns a new state, and thus allows modeling a *mutable* environment.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Note that this monad takes a type parameter, the type of the state information.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] do-blocks in a state monad are sequences of operations that can examine and update the state data.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Informally, a state monad of state type S maps the type of return values T into functions of type $S\rightarrow T\times S$ , where S is the underlying state.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] From the category theory point of view, a state monad is derived from the adjunction between the product functor and the exponential functor, which exists in any cartesian closed category by definition.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A continuation monad with return type R maps type T into functions of type $\left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R$ .
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] It is used to model continuation-passing style.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] That is, both functions take in an integer and return another integer.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Where the result is the result of `foo` applied to the result of `bar` applied to `x`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] But suppose we are debugging our program, and we would like to add logging messages to `foo` and `bar`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] So that both functions return a tuple, with the result of the application as the integer, and a logging message with information about the applied function and all the previously applied functions as the string.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Unfortunately, this means we can no longer compose `foo` and `bar`, as their input type `int` is not compatible with their output type `int * string`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] And although we can again gain composability by modifying the types of each function to be `int * string -> int * string`, this would require us to add boilerplate code to each function to extract the integer from the tuple, which would get tedious as the number of such functions increases.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `bind` takes in an integer and string tuple, then takes in a function (like `foo`) that maps from an integer to an integer and string tuple.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Its output is an integer and string tuple, which is the result of applying the input function to the integer within the input integer and string tuple.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In this way, we only need to write boilerplate code to extract the integer from the tuple once, in `bind`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Now we have regained some composability.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Where `(x,s)` is an integer and string tuple.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] So that `t >>= f` is the same as `bind t f`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Finally, we define a new function to avoid writing `(x, "")` every time we wish to create an empty logging message, where `""` is the empty string.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Which wraps `x` in the tuple described above.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] That allows us to more easily log the effects of `bar` and `foo` on `x`.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `int * string` denotes a pseudo-coded **monadic value**.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `bind` and `return` are analogous to the corresponding functions of the same name.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In fact, `int * string`, `bind`, and `return` form a monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] An **additive monad** is a monad endowed with an additional closed, associative, binary operator **mplus** and an identity element under mplus, called **mzero**.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` monad can be considered additive, with `Nothing` as mzero and a variation on the OR operator as mplus.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `List` is also an additive monad, with the empty list `[]` acting as mzero and the concatenation operator `++` as mplus.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Intuitively, mzero represents a monadic wrapper with no value from an underlying type, but is also considered a "zero" (rather than a "one") since it acts as an absorber for bind, returning mzero whenever bound to a monadic function.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This property is two-sided, and bind will also return mzero when any value is bound to a monadic zero function.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In category-theoretic terms, an additive monad qualifies once as a monoid over monadic functions with bind (as all monads do), and again over monadic values via mplus.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, the general outline of a monad may be useful, but no simple pattern recommends one monad or another.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] This is where a **free monad** comes in; as a free object in the category of monads, it can represent monadic structure without any specific constraints beyond the monad laws themselves.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Just as a free monoid concatenates elements without evaluation, a free monad allows chaining computations with markers to satisfy the type system, but otherwise imposes no deeper semantics itself.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] For example, by working entirely through the `Just` and `Nothing` markers, the `Maybe` monad is in fact a free monad.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] The `List` monad, on the other hand, is not a free monad since it brings extra, specific facts about lists (like append) into its definition.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Free monads, however, are *not* restricted to a linked-list like in this example, and can be built around other structures like trees.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Using free monads intentionally may seem impractical at first, but their formal nature is particularly well-suited for syntactic problems.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A free monad can be used to track syntax and type while leaving semantics for later, and has found use in parsers and interpreters as a result.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Others have applied them to more dynamic, operational problems too, such as providing iteratees within a language.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Besides generating monads with extra properties, for any given monad, one can also define a **comonad**.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Conceptually, if monads represent computations built up from underlying values, then comonads can be seen as reductions back down to values.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code, in a sense, cannot be fully "unpacked"; once a value is wrapped within a monad, it remains quarantined there along with any side-effects (a good thing in purely functional programming).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes though, a problem is more about consuming contextual data, which comonads can model explicitly.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Technically, a comonad is the categorical dual of a monad, which loosely means that it will have the same required components, only with the direction of the type signatures *reversed*.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] While operations like extend are reversed, however, a comonad does *not* reverse functions it acts on, and consequently, comonads are still functors with map, not cofunctors.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A simple example is the **Product comonad**, which outputs values based on an input value and shared environment data.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In fact, the `Product` comonad is just the dual of the `Writer` monad and effectively the same as the `Reader` monad (both discussed below).
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] `Product` and `Reader` differ only in which function signatures they accept, and how they complement those functions by wrapping or unwrapping values.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] A less trivial example is the **Stream comonad**, which can be used to represent data streams and attach filters to the incoming signals with extend.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] In fact, while not as popular as monads, researchers have found comonads particularly useful for stream processing and modeling dataflow programming.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] Due to their strict definitions, however, one cannot simply move objects back and forth between monads and comonads.
[src:effect-systems/monad-functional-programming] As an even higher abstraction, arrows can subsume both structures, but finding more granular ways to combine monadic and comonadic code is an active area of research.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:effect-systems/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] In analytic philosophy and computer science, **referential transparency** and **referential opacity** are properties of linguistic constructions, and by extension of languages.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] A linguistic construction is called *referentially transparent* when for any expression built from it, replacing a subexpression with another one that denotes the same value does not change the value of the expression.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Otherwise, it is called *referentially opaque*.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Referential transparency, in programming languages, depends on semantic equivalences among denotations of expressions, or on contextual equivalence of expressions themselves.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] That is, referential transparency depends on the semantics of the language.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] So, both declarative languages and imperative languages can have referentially transparent positions, referentially opaque positions, or (usually) both, according to the semantics they are given.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] The importance of referentially transparent positions is that they allow the programmer and the compiler to reason about program behavior as a rewrite system at those positions.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] This can help in proving correctness, simplifying an algorithm, assisting in modifying code without breaking it, or optimizing code by means of memoization, common subexpression elimination, lazy evaluation, constant folding, or parallelization.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] There are three fundamental properties concerning substitutivity in formal languages: referential transparency, definiteness, and unfoldability.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Let’s denote syntactic equivalence with ≡ and semantic equivalence with =.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] A *position* is defined by a sequence of natural numbers.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] The empty sequence is denoted by ε and the sequence constructor by ‘.’.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] In other words, a position is purely referential in an expression if and only if it is subject to the substitutivity of equals. ε is purely referential in all expressions.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Otherwise Ω is *referentially opaque* in place i.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] An operator is *referentially transparent* is defined by it is referentially transparent in all places.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] A formal language is *referentially transparent* is defined by all its operators are referentially transparent.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Indeed, the second position is purely referential in the assertion because substituting *The capital of the United Kingdom* for *London* does not change the value of the assertion.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] The first position is also purely referential for the same substitutivity reason.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Indeed, the first position is not purely referential in the statement because substituting *The capital of the United Kingdom* for *London* changes the value of the statement and the quotation.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] So in the first position, the ‘_ contains _’ and quote operators destroy the relation between an expression and the value that it denotes.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] ‘London’ refers to the largest city of the United Kingdom.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Indeed, the first position is purely referential in the statement, though it is not in the quotation, because substituting *The capital of the United Kingdom* for *London* does not change the value of the statement.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] So in the first position, the ‘_ refers to _’ operator restores the relation between an expression and the value that it denotes.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] The second position is also purely referential for the same substitutivity reason.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] A formal language is *definite* is defined by all the occurrences of a variable within its scope denote the same value.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Indeed, the two occurrences of x denote the same value.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] A formal language is *unfoldable* is defined by all expressions are β-reducible.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Referential transparency, definiteness, and unfoldability are independent.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Definiteness implies unfoldability only for deterministic languages.
[src:effect-systems/referential-transparency] Non-deterministic languages cannot have definiteness and unfoldability at the same time.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] In computer science, an operation or expression is said to have a **side effect** if it has any observable effect other than its primary effect of reading the value of its arguments and returning a value to the invoker of the operation.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Example side effects include modifying a non-local variable, a static local variable or a mutable argument passed by reference; performing I/O; or calling other functions with side-effects.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] In the presence of side effects, a program's behaviour may depend on history; that is, the order of evaluation matters.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Understanding and debugging a function with side effects requires knowledge about the context and its possible histories.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Side effects play an important role in the design and analysis of programming languages.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] The degree to which side effects are used depends on the programming paradigm.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] For example, imperative programming is commonly used to produce side effects, to update a system's state.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] By contrast, declarative programming is commonly used to report on the state of system, without side effects.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Functional programming aims to minimize or eliminate side effects.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] The lack of side effects makes it easier to do formal verification of a program.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] The functional language Haskell eliminates side effects such as I/O and other stateful computations by replacing them with monadic actions.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Functional languages such as Standard ML, Scheme and Scala do not restrict side effects, but it is customary for programmers to avoid them.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Effect systems extend types to keep track of effects, permitting concise notation for functions with effects, while maintaining information about the extent and nature of side effects.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] In particular, functions without effects correspond to pure functions.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Assembly language programmers must be aware of *hidden* side effects—instructions that modify parts of the processor state which are not mentioned in the instruction's mnemonic.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] A classic example of a hidden side effect is an arithmetic instruction that implicitly modifies condition codes (a hidden side effect) while it explicitly modifies a register (the intended effect).
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] One potential drawback of an instruction set with hidden side effects is that, if many instructions have side effects on a single piece of state, like condition codes, then the logic required to update that state sequentially may become a performance bottleneck.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] The problem is particularly acute on some processors designed with pipelining (since 1990) or with out-of-order execution.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Such a processor may require additional control circuitry to detect hidden side effects and stall the pipeline if the next instruction depends on the results of those effects.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Absence of side effects is a necessary, but not sufficient, condition for referential transparency.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Referential transparency means that an expression (such as a function) can be replaced with its value.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] This requires that the expression is pure, that is to say the expression must be deterministic (always give the same value for the same input) and side-effect free.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] Side effects caused by the time taken for an operation to execute are usually ignored when discussing side effects and referential transparency.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] There are some cases, such as with hardware timing or testing, where operations are inserted specifically for their temporal side effects e.g.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] These instructions do not change state other than taking an amount of time to complete.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] A subroutine with side effects is idempotent if multiple calls of the subroutine have the same effect on the system state as a single call, in other words if the function from the system state space to itself associated with the subroutine is idempotent in the mathematical sense.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] `setx` is idempotent because the second call of `setx` to 3 has the same effect on the system state as the first call: `x` was already set to 3 after the first call, and it is still set to 3 after the second call.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] A pure function is idempotent if it is idempotent in the mathematical sense.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] `abs` is idempotent because the second call of `abs` to the return value of the first call to -3 returns the same value as the first call to -3.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] One common demonstration of side effect behavior is that of the assignment operator in C.
[src:effect-systems/side-effect-computer-science] The assignment `a = b` is an expression that evaluates to the same value as the expression `b`, with the side effect of storing the R-value of `b` into the L-value of `a`.
